<span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Sokl wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Amelie is one of my all time favourite films, .. of all time <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /></td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />
 
<br />
Mine too. Its a super film. 
<br />
 
<br />
Hidden Castle - old black and white Japanese samurai movie 
<br />
Ran (Orchid) also from Japan. 
<br />
Red Lantern - as mentioned above 
<br />

<br />
Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon
<br />

<br />
All of the Jackie Chan movies.
<br />
 
<br />
Das Boat - as mentioned above 
<br />
 
<br />
Atanarjuat: The Fast Runner  - Canadian film by the National Film Board, about Inuit (Eskimo) life when evil shaman come to your village. Filmed in Inuktitut, directed by Inuit filmmakers. It won several awards. 
<br />
 
<br />
The Man Who Planted Trees - one of my favorite animation movies. Hard as heck to find though.  Its the story of 50 years of change in an area that were the result of a shepard who continuously planted trees. As the forest grew and changed the area, the people and economy of the area changed as well. The narrator of the movie was the single person to see the ties between the efforts of the shepard, and the changes to the community.  I do believe the narration is available in english or french, but the version I saw long ago was in original French with english subtitles.
<br />

<br />
ps. Your spellchecker doesn't recognise the word "Atanarjuat". lol, who would have thought?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
